#### **Connecting n8n to Claude Desktop**

I have to preface this by saying that when I connected n8n and Claude about a month ago, I was using earlier versions of both tools, which looked quite different from what we have now.

But that‚Äôs the exciting part of the automations. Things change frequently, so you end up learning new and better ways of doing things almost every day, even within the same workflow.

With that in mind, I recommend checking the n8n docs for the [latest guidance](https://docs.n8n.io/advanced-ai/accessing-n8n-mcp-server/) on accessing their MCP server, as that will be most relevant to current installations.

There are two ways of setting up MCP authentication: OAuth and Access Token. I only tried the Access Token approach, but OAuth does seem to be a bit more straightforward at first glance (if you know what you‚Äôre doing).

I will share some of my learnings in case they are still relevant, or if you are working with older versions. Here are some ‚Äúpotentially outdated but still useful‚Äù pointers:

**Make sure you have [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/en/download) installed and added to PATH:** You need both Node and npx. You can check if they are installed and where they live by running the following in your command line:  
node \-v  
npx \-v

1. where npx  
    If installed correctly, the current versions will show up, and npx should be located at:  
   C:\\Program Files\\nodejs\\npx.cmd  
2. **Reboot after the Node.js installation and restart Claude Desktop:** This helps Claude pick up PATH changes.

**In the claude\_desktop\_config.json file, add:**  
{  
  "mcpServers": {  
    "n8n-mcp": {  
      "command": "cmd.exe",  
      "args": \[  
        "/c",  
        "npx",  
        "-y",  
        "supergateway",  
        "--streamableHttp",  
        "\<YOUR\_SERVER\_URL\>",  
        "--header",  
        "authorization: Bearer \<YOUR\_ACCESS\_TOKEN\_HERE\>"  
      \]  
    }  
  }  
}  
Notice that it is slightly different from the configuration n8n suggests:  
{  
  "mcpServers": {  
    "n8n-mcp": {  
      "command": "npx",  
      "args": \[  
        "-y",  
        "supergateway",  
        "--streamableHttp",  
        "\<YOUR\_SERVER\_URL\>",  
        "--header",  
        "authorization:Bearer \<YOUR\_ACCESS\_TOKEN\_HERE\>"  
      \]  
    }  
  }

3. }  
   For some reason, Windows was failing to resolve the executable path for npx, so I had to call it via **cmd.exe** with **/c**. This [appears](https://github.com/SuperClaude-Org/SuperClaude_Framework/issues/390) to be Windows-specific and may already be fixed in newer versions of n8n or Claude Desktop, but I'm including it anyway.

Once connected, you should see **n8n-mcp** in Claude Desktop under **Settings ‚Üí Connectors**:

![The Claude Desktop settings menu, showing "Connectors" for integrating services like Google Drive, Gmail, Slack, and GitHub. n8n-mcp (local dev) is shown as configured. Options include "Connect" buttons and a "Configure" option.][image3]

You can then enable the MCP access for individual published workflows:

![An n8n software interface displaying a visual content testing workflow with a production checklist. The checklist on the right mentions tasks like setting error notifications, tracking time saved, and enabling MCP access. Various coloured sections contain detailed instructions and workflow steps, indicating a structured, organised system.][image4]

If you don‚Äôt see the **Enable MCP access** option, you‚Äôre likely using a currently unsupported trigger node. At the time of writing, MCP access only works with these trigger nodes:

* Schedule  
* Webhook  
* Form  
* Chat

For the visual system testing, we are using a Schedule trigger, so everything should connect properly.

To start troubleshooting (or just discussing) the workflow with Claude, you can type something like:

Use n8n MCP to inspect workflow `<workflow name or id>`. Find why the last execution failed and propose a fix.

Or you can jump straight into the specific issue you want help with. No need for verbose explanations or workflow screenshots, which makes this a whole lot quicker.

Try it, and thank me later üòã\!

#### **Workaround 1: LATE API in n8n**

It‚Äôs hard to believe that in this day and age, some questions still cannot be solved with a quick Google, but alas. My initial attempts to find alternatives for Pinterest access with Claude, ChatGPT, and Google were not proving fruitful.

Until I came across a small Reddit thread, where the OP had exactly the same concern as I did about the Standard Access tokens. And luckily, one of the commenters had a solution: an [**n8n community node for the LATE API**](https://www.npmjs.com/package/n8n-nodes-late).

After a slightly convoluted installation process, I discovered that this node supported most major social media platforms (X, Instagram, Facebook, LinkedIn, YouTube, TikTok, Threads), but not Pinterest ü´†.

Alena, read the docs before you install\!\!\!

But not all was lost. After creating an account on the [**LATE website**](https://getlate.dev/), I saw that Pinterest integration is supported directly through their API.

You can create a free account and an API key, which currently allows **20 free posts/mo** across 2 social media profiles (it was only 10 posts/mo when I started testing last month üòÆ).

This made the setup easier than expected. All I needed to do was update the HTTP node (**Node 8a** from [**Workflow 2**](https://savvysloth.substack.com/i/186058873/workflow-2-daily-pin-creation)) that previously called the Pinterest API to call the LATE API instead.

After some faffing around with the configurations from the [**LATE Pinterest docs**](https://docs.getlate.dev/platforms/pinterest), I finally came up with the following setup:

---

##### **Node 8a: If Approved, Upload Pin to Pinterest with LATE API**

* **Node type:** HTTP Request  
* **Method:** POST  
* **Configuration:**  
  * **URL:** `https://getlate.dev/api/v1/posts`  
  * **Send Headers:** Enable  
  * **Headers:**  
    * `Authorization`: `Bearer YOUR_LATE_API_KEY`  
    * `Content-Type`: `application/json`  
  * **Send Body:** Enable  
  * **Body Content Type:** JSON  
  * **Specify Body:** Using JSON

{  
  "content": "{{ $('Select a random image to create').item.json.pin\_description }}",  
  "mediaItems": \[  
    {  
      "type": "image",  
      "url": "{{ 'https://gen.pollinations.ai/image/' \+ encodeURIComponent($('Select a random image to create').item.json.image\_prompt) \+ '/?width=1000\&height=1500\&model=flux\&key=YOUR\_API\_KEY' }}"  
    }  
  \],  
  "platforms": \[  
    {  
      "platform": "pinterest",  
      "accountId": "YOUR\_LATE\_PROFILE\_ID",  
      "platformSpecificData": {  
        "title": "{{ $('Select a random image to create').item.json.pin\_title }}",  
        "boardId": "{{ $('Select a random image to create').item.json.board\_id }}",  
        "altText": "{{ $('Select a random image to create').item.json.alt\_text }}",  
        "description": "{{ $('Select a random image to create').item.json.pin\_description }}",  
        "link": ""  
      }  
    }  
  \],  
  "publishNow": true  
}

* **Settings:**  
  * **Retry On Fail:** Enable  
  * **Max. Tries:** 3  
  * **Wait Between Tries (ms):** 5000

---

Note that for the **accountId** parameter, you need your LATE profile ID, not the Pinterest account ID. You will find it under **Dashboard ‚Üí Connections ‚Üí Pinterest**:

![The LATE dashboard showing social media integration options: Threads, Bluesky, Pinterest, Reddit, Google Business, Telegram, and Snapchat. Connection buttons are visible. Pinterest ID is highlighted with a dark blue box.][image5]

The rest of the nodes stayed mostly the same, with one small change to how the **pin ID** is extracted in **Node 9**. It now needs to be parsed from the pin URL:

* `pin_id`: `{{ $json.post.platforms[0].platformPostUrl.split('/pin/')[1].replace('/', '') }}`

And that‚Äôs pretty much it. You can now actually post your AI-generated pins for the world to see\!

Better yet, LATE provides an [**analytics add-on**](https://docs.getlate.dev/pricing) for only **$1/profile/mo** for **any paid plan**. If you already use LATE and want automated analytics collection, this could be a good way to extend the workflow. I haven‚Äôt explored the setup myself, but I imagine you can repurpose the [**Workflow 2 extension**](https://savvysloth.substack.com/i/186058873/workflow-2-extension-analytics-collection-optional) for analytics with LATE.

**A word of caution:** The LATE free tier is limited. Even at 20 posts/mo, you still won‚Äôt be able to post a pin a day for the whole month (unless you create multiple free accounts, but who would do that üëÄ).

I also slightly updated Workflow 1 to match this version of Workflow 2\. This time, you need to create the Pinterest boards manually first, and then use Workflow 1 with the Pinterest Production Access token and `https://api.pinterest.com/v5/boards` URL to retrieve board IDs:

#### **Workaround 2: New Workflow in Make**

While researching Pinterest access solutions, I came across the n8n community forum. Someone was complaining that they could create pins in Make without API keys, but not in n8n, and requested n8n to add a similar node (n8n, pretty please).

That led me to my next big idea: rebuild the whole thing in [**Make**](https://www.make.com/en).

![Make scenario illustrating Pinterest pin creation from Google Sheets using automation. Icons represent steps like image selection, email triggers, and scheduling.][image7]

The overall structure of this workflow, or scenario in Make terms, is very similar to the n8n version, so I won‚Äôt go into the same level of detail. But there are a few differences worth pointing out:

**No schedule trigger:** In Make, you set the time you want the scenario to be initiated at the bottom of your screen rather than using a dedicated trigger module.

**No code module with free plan:** Since I couldn‚Äôt use JavaScript to pick a random unpublished item, I modified the **content\_queue** sheet to include a **random\_value** column (add this in column O) using `=RAND()` formula:

![A Google Sheet titled "Visual Systems Testing" with columns for alt-text descriptions, status, platform, board ID, and random values. Rows contain humorous cartoon themes and numerical data.][image8]

Every time the sheet is accessed, the random numbers change. The first **Google Sheet module** just picks the row with the lowest value in that given instance:

---

**Filter:** posted (K) / Text operators: Equal to / FALSE

**Order by:** random\_value (O)

**Field Type:** Number

**Sort order:** Ascending (or Descending, it doesn‚Äôt really matter)

**Limit:** 1

---

**No human-in-the-loop feature:** Make doesn‚Äôt have a direct equivalent of the ‚ÄúSend and Wait for Response‚Äù node; to best simulate this functionality, I‚Äôve done the following:

1. **Gmail request approval module:** Sends the email with the pin image and details to the reviewer‚Äôs email, with a request to reply with either **APPROVE** or **DECLINE**.  
2. **Sleep for 4 minutes module:** Pauses the scenario for 240 seconds. The maximum you can wait for with a single Sleep module is 5 minutes. With free plans, the maximum scenario execution time is 5 minutes total, but on the paid plans, you can extend the delay by chaining several Sleep modules together.  
3. **Get the email response module:** Fetches the latest unread email reply with the subject line ‚ÄúRe: Pinterest Image \+ Pin Approval Request (Make)‚Äú from the reviewer‚Äôs email.  
4. **Extract the email response module:** Text parser in Make uses the regex pattern ‚Äú^(APPROVE|DECLINE)‚Äú to extract the reviewer‚Äôs answer and direct the flow accordingly.

**Specialised Pinterest module:** That‚Äôs the star of the show. You just connect your Pinterest account, fill in the required fields, and post as many pins as you like. No access tokens or APIs required.

#### **Pollinations.ai Access Update**

If you‚Äôve been paying attention, you might‚Äôve noticed earlier in the n8n node configuration that the Pollinations.ai endpoint has changed slightly compared to last week‚Äôs post from:

https://image.pollinations.ai/prompt/{{ encodeURIComponent($json.image\_prompt) }}/?width=1000\&height=1500\&model=flux

to:

https://gen.pollinations.ai/image/{{ encodeURIComponent($json.image\_prompt) }}/?width=1000\&height=1500\&model=flux\&key=YOUR\_API\_KEY

And yes, you now need a Pollinations.ai API key to generate images. What can I say, another week, another heartbreak üíî.

The previous endpoint worked fine for me until early February, at which point all my workflows started throwing the **502 Bad Gateway** errors:

![Screenshot of an n8n workflow interface for generating images using Pollinations.ai, displaying input settings, URL parameters, and error messages indicating a 'Bad gateway' issue with the service. The interface has sections for parameters and output and various tabs like 'Schema' and 'JSON'.][image9]

Having done some digging, I discovered that Pollinations.ai have been migrating to a new endpoint since December, and the transition now seems complete.

Luckily, you can still get the API key with some free credits, although we will have to see how this might change over time.

That‚Äôs real-life automation for you: there‚Äôs always room for improvement, and something is bound to break at some point, even if it currently works.
